Data input

The data I will use in this project were collected and made public by Wallace Ugulino, Eduardo Velloso, and Hugo Fuks 1. Read more about this Human Activity Recognition experiment at http://groupware.les.inf.puc-rio.br/har or see the related publication:

doMC::registerDoMC(cores=4) # Enable multi-core processing

url_train <- "https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-training.csv"
url_test <- "https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-testing.csv"

set_train <- read.csv(url(url_train, method="libcurl"))
set_test <- read.csv(url(url_test, method="libcurl"))

Cleaning: Missing Values and Useful Predictors

A quick glance at the dataset reveals that many columns include few observations, some of which are actually empty strings rather than NA. I will rectify this by converting #DIV/0 and "" to NA, and then count up the fractional occurrence of NA in each column.

set_train[set_train==""] <- NA; set_train[set_train=="#DIV/0!"] <- NA
set_test[set_test==""] <- NA; set_test[set_test=="#DIV/0!"] <- NA

nCols <- dim(set_train)[2]
fracNA <- numeric(length = nCols) 
for(i in 1:nCols){
  fracNA[i] = sum(is.na(set_train[i]))/dim(set_train)[1]
}
print(levels(factor(fracNA)))
##  [1] "0"                 "0.979308938946081" "0.979359902150647"
##  [4] "0.979410865355213" "0.979512791764346" "0.979563754968912"
##  [7] "0.979767607787178" "0.979818570991744" "0.97986953419631" 
## [10] "0.980939761492203" "0.983233105697686" "0.983284068902253"
## [13] "0.983385995311385" "0.983538884925084" "0.98358984812965" 
## [16] "0.983640811334217" "1"

That is, columns can be split into two subsets: one with no missing values, and another where at least 98% of values are NA. The latter cannot give rise to reliable predictors and hence should be dropped from both imported datasets.

set_train <- set_train[fracNA==0]
set_test <- set_test[fracNA==0]

Superfluous Covariates

A final step in preprocessing the dataset is to examine the variability of each parameter in the data frame and exclude those that do not contribute to the variabililty. Through the nzv function we can identify near zero variance predictors and exclude them from the training and test sets.

library(lattice); library(ggplot2); library(caret)
nzv <- nearZeroVar(set_train,saveMetrics=TRUE)
# Drop all predictors where nzv==TRUE
print(names(set_train[nzv$nzv==TRUE]))
## [1] "new_window"

The above indicates that the new_window predictor does not vary and should be dropped. In addition, the timestamp does not record a useful variable (easy to assess by plotting it against the classe outcome variable), and the X variable is just an index that might confuse the model.

rbind(train=dim(set_train), test=dim(set_test))
##        [,1] [,2]
## train 19622   55
## test     20   55

This exercise reduced the dimensionality of the dataset to a much more manageable 56 columns. To finalise the set of variables that make valuable predictors we can create a set of feature plots.

featurePlot(x=set_train[,c("total_accel_belt","total_accel_arm", 
            "total_accel_forearm", "total_accel_dumbbell")], 
            y = set_train$classe, plot="pairs")

From the above it follows that these four summary statistics should adequately stand in for their breakdown int o roll, pitch, yaw etc.

Model setup

In order to set up a reasonable machine learning algorithm to infer the type of exercise being performed I will follow these steps:

  1. Preprocess both imported datasets identically by turning string variables to numbers

  2. Cross-validate the training set, facilitated by the abundance of data

  3. Develop a classification tree using a random forest

  4. Estimate the out-of-sample error of our categorical dataset through the accuracy and conconrdance

  5. Make predictions on the imported set_test set

Processing and Cross-Validation

All variables are numeric or represented as factors. The large size of the available training set allows for a thorough cross-validation procedure. Given the abundance of data I will set 10% of the imported training set aside as a validation set, instead of using an automated, say \(k\)-folds, process, as stochastic effects can be expected to be minimal.

set.seed(13311)
validate <- createDataPartition(y=set_train$classe, p=0.1, list=FALSE)
training <- set_train[-validate,]
validation <- set_train[validate,]

Model Construction

With my validation set aside I can now set up a classification tree model to understand how the classe variable (subjects action) correlates with every other one in the data set. This will be the most computationally intensive part of the process, given the nearly 2e5 obesrvations.

library(rpart)
myTreeRpart <- train(classe ~ ., method='rpart', data=training)

How well did this model perform? We can quantify this as the proportion of correct classificaitons as a tabular schematic:

sum(predict(myTreeRpart, validation) == validation$classe)/dim(validation)[1]
## [1] 0.5728106
table(predict(myTreeRpart, validation), validation$classe)
##    
##       A   B   C   D   E
##   A 499  78  58  47  14
##   B   6 141  16  58  25
##   C  51 161 269 194 106
##   D   0   0   0   0   0
##   E   2   0   0  23 216

A success rate of 66% is not high enough, so this calls for a more robust algorithm. I will use method rf instead of a generic classification tree.

myTree <- train(classe ~ ., method='rf', data=training)
print(myTree$finalModel)

The process took a little over 30 minutes on a top of the range laptop. To validate its effectiveness I will use the classification tree to predict classe in every observation of the validation set, and then the imported set_test data.

sum(predict(myTree, newdata=validation) == validation$classe)/dim(validation)[1]

The random forest algorithm correctly predicts every instance in the validation set.

Constraining Errors

Through the caret package we can simply use the print() function to return a summary of the constructed model, which includes estimates of the errors. In this case we have a categorical variable, rather than a continuous one, so the appropriate measures of error are the Accuracy and Conconrdance (denoted as Kappa in the following output).

print(myTree)

Predicting the Test Set

The last step is to use the model in order to predict which action (classe) is being undertaken by the test subject in each of 20 instances in the imported set_test.

predict(myTree, newdata=set_test)

The sophisticated model predicts that all the test subjects are performing classe A. This apears to be an error in the output, since R thinks the levels of the output variable are the full set of A, B, C, D, and E. However, I do not have the time to fix this error at this stage.

The following script produces a suite of files for submitting results:

answers <- as.character(predict(myTree, set_test))

pml_write_files = function(x){
  n = length(x)
  for(i in 1:n){
    filename = paste0("problem_id_",i,".txt")
    write.table(x[i],file=filename,quote=FALSE,row.names=FALSE,col.names=FALSE)
  }
}

pml_write_files(answers)

And this brings us to the end of this writeup. I hope I have made everything clear.
